   <titleInfo>
      <title>Letter, John Shrady in Camp near Somerset, Ky., to Jeannie Shrady in New York, N.Y., 1863 May 17</title>
   </titleInfo>
   <abstract>In this letter, dated May 17, 1863, from camp near Somerset, Ky., John Shrady, a regimental surgeon, writes to his wife, Jeannie, in New York City, outlining his activities between May 5th and May 17th in a diary format. Among the occasions, he reports that 33 Union soldiers died attempting to cross a river at a place called "Stigall's Ferry." Most of the news is of a personal nature to Dr. Shrady, and he describes the weather, a "Lodge" meeting, and his belief that an "avenging Nemesis" has caused him to live in "exile" from home. The letter appears to be incomplete.</abstract>
